<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-568-436  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 568 436.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  June 1990 v8 n6 p84(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber-optic LANs improve in price and performance. (local areanetworks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Greenstein, Irwin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic in early 1990 is cheaper than ever and installation offiber-optic gives a company a physical migration path from the10-Mbps Ethernet to 100-Mbps Field Distribution Data Interface(FDDI).andP;  An industry analyst with Dataquest expects thefiber-optic Ethernet market to have a 36.7 percent compound annualgrowth rate (CAGR) between 1988 and 1993.andP;  Coaxial Ethernet has aprojected CAGR of 7.2 percent and unshielded twisted pair a CAGRof 82.7 percent.andP;  Fiber optics in local area networks (LANs) willbe one of the faster growing segments of the LAN market.andP;  The costof chip sets and other components does affect the price andperformance of fiber-optic LAN products.andP;  There are 7 advantagesof fiber-optic LANs: security, low signal attenuation anddistortion, protection against electromagnetic interference andlightning bolts, safety, reliability, bandwidth, and size andweight.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksEthernetFiber OpticsFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardMarket SharePricePerformance.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   U.S. sales of multimedia fiber-optic components by type,1988-1994. (chart)Fiber-optic LAN market penetration by product, 1987-1993. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>